page.text: The purpose of this study is to evaluate the traffic impact that will result from a proposed high
school development located northwest of the intersection at Post Oak Tritt Road / Holly Springs
Road in Cobb County. The property is currently owned by the Marcus Jewish Community
Center of Atlanta; however, the community center was not being used at the time of this
analysis. During the traffic data collection, the driveway to the site was gated and closed. The
Mount Bethel Christian Academy is proposing the use of the property and its buildings for a
private high school, which is planned to have a maximum enrollment of no more than 625
students. The location of the proposed development and the surrounding roadway network is
In this study, the AM and PM peak hours have been analyzed. This study includes the evaluation
of the existing and future traffic operations at the intersections of:
Post Oak Tritt Road / Holly Springs Road
Post Oak Tritt Road / Site Driveway (Community Center Driveway) / Gelding Lane
Post Oak Tritt Road / Hampton Park Drive
Recommendations to improve traffic operations have been identified, where appropriate.

text.b: E T H O D O L O G Y

page.text: In this study, the methodology used for evaluating traffic operations at each of the subject
intersections is based on the criteria set forth in the Transportation Research Board’s Highway
Capacity Manual, 2000 edition (HCM 2000). Synchro software, which utilizes the HCM 2000
methodology, was used for the analysis. The following is a description of the methodology
employed for the analysis of unsignalized and signalized intersections.

text.b: U n s i g n a l i z e d I n t e r s e c t i o n s

page.text: For unsignalized intersections at which the side street or minor street is controlled by a stop sign,
the criteria for evaluating traffic operations are the level of service (LOS) for the turning
movements at the intersection and the level of service for the overall intersection. Level of
service is based on the average controlled delay incurred at the intersection. Controlled delay for
unsignalized intersections includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped
delay, and final acceleration delay. Several factors affect the controlled delay for unsignalized
intersections, such as the availability and distribution of gaps in the conflicting traffic stream,
critical gaps, and follow-up time for a vehicle in the queue.
Level of service is assigned a letter designation from A through F. Level of service A indicates
excellent operations with little delay to motorists, while level of service F exists when there are
insufficient gaps of acceptable size to allow vehicles on the side street to cross safely, resulting
in extremely long total delays and long queues. The level of service criteria for two-way stop-
controlled and all-way stop-controlled (unsignalized) intersections is given in Table 1.
Level of Service Criteria for Unsignalized

text.b: S i g n a l i z e d I n t e r s e c t i o n s

page.text: For signalized intersections, it is necessary to evaluate both capacity and level of service in order
to evaluate the overall operation of the intersection. The capacity analysis of an intersection is
performed by comparing the volume of traffic using the various lane groups at the intersection to
the capacity of those lane groups. This results in a volume/capacity (v/c) ratio for each lane
group. A v/c ratio greater than 1.0 indicates that the volume of traffic has exceeded the capacity
available, resulting in a temporary excess of demand. Although the capacity of the entire
intersection is not defined, a composite v/c ratio for the sum of the critical lane groups within the
intersection is computed. This composite v/c ratio is an indication of the overall intersection
Level of service for a signalized intersection is defined in terms of average controlled delay per
vehicle, which is composed of initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay, and
final acceleration delay. The levels of service criteria for signalized intersections, based on
average controlled delay, are shown in Table 2. Level of service A indicates operations with very
low controlled delay, while level of service F describes operations with extremely high average
controlled delay. Level of service E is typically considered to be the limit of acceptable delay,
and level of service F is considered unacceptable by most drivers.

Turning movement counts were collected on Tuesday, August 13, 2013. All turning movement
counts were recorded during the AM, PM & School PM peak hours between 7:00 a.m. to 9:00
a.m., 4:45p.m. to 5:45 p.m., and 3:00 to 4:00 p.m., respectively. The four consecutive 15-minute
interval volumes that summed to produce the highest volume at the intersections were then
determined. These volumes make up the peak hour traffic volumes for the intersections counted

page.text: The results of the existing conditions analysis indicate that the intersection of Post Oak Tritt
Road / Holly Springs Road currently operates at LOS “E” in both the AM and PM peak hours.
This indicates that some approaches to the intersection are nearing capacity with stop-and-go
delays and queuing. More specifically, this is seen in the predominantly southbound and
eastbound approaches during the morning peak and the northbound and eastbound approaches in
the evening peak. Queuing in the eastbound direction along Post Oak Tritt is calculated to extend
50% of the distance from Holly Springs Road to the site driveway in the morning.
The delays at the intersection of Post Oak Tritt Rd / Holly Springs Rd are lesser during the
“School PM Peak Hour” as the majority of work-home trips have yet to enter the roadway. Even
though school traffic is higher during this time period, impacts are not as significant as in the
other peak hours when more vehicles are on the roadway.
Minimal delays and queues are seen on the stop-controlled side-street approaches to Post Oak
Tritt Road from Gelding Lane and Hampton Park Drive.

text.b: R A F F I C
P E R A T I O N S

page.text: In order to evaluate future traffic operations in this area, a projection was made of future base
year traffic volumes. The Georgia Department of Transportation recorded average daily traffic
volumes at several locations in the vicinity of the site. Reviewing the growth over the last several
years revealed growth of approximately 1% in the area. This growth factor was applied to the
existing traffic volumes on the roadways in order to estimate the amount of background traffic
that will be present on the roadway by the year 2015, prior to the addition of site-generated
traffic from the school. The site generated traffic volumes (shown in Figure 6) were added to
calculate the Future 2015 traffic volumes. The resulting total future peak hour volumes are
shown in Figure 7. These volumes were used to analyze future traffic operations at all the study
intersections. The results of the analysis are shown in Table 5.

text.b: O N C L U S I O N S A N D
E C O M M E N D A T I O N S

page.text: Traffic operations were evaluated for a proposed high school development located on the Marcus
Jewish Community Center of Atlanta property on Post Oak Tritt Rd. Mt. Bethel Christian
Academy is planning to use the facility as a private high school with a maximum enrollment of
625 students. The analysis is divided into three time periods based on the hours of operation for
the school and the peak travel times identified in the traffic count data, morning peak hour
(7:15am-8:15am), School Peak (3:00pm-4:00pm), and evening peak hour (4:45pm-5:45pm).
Potential traffic operation issues for each of study intersections are identified below:
Post Oak Tritt Road / Holly Springs Road
An analysis of the existing conditions indicated that there are pronounced delays at this
intersection in the morning and evening peak periods. The delays at this signalized intersection
in the morning are predominantly in the southbound and eastbound directions, while delays in
the evening are in the northbound and eastbound directions. Delays at these times are classified
as level-of-service “E”, which is to say that the approaches are nearing capacity with some stop-
and-go delays and queues. The queues in the eastbound direction are calculated to extend 50% of
the distance between Holly Springs Rd and the Site Driveway. There are not heavy delays during
the school peak period analyzed (3-4pm) as the traffic volumes along the road network at this
time are a fraction of those in the morning and evening peak periods.
Due to the site added traffic, the intersection will see moderate increases in delay in the morning
(20 second increase for the average vehicle) but will continue to operate at an overall level-of-
service “E” for this time period. Queues will extend to 60% of distance between Holly Springs
and Site Driveway. Impacts are minor in the afternoon and evening peak periods because the
school traffic and evening traffic are not coinciding at the same time (as they do in the morning).
The existing conditions analysis indicates that there are short delays and queuing on these stop-
controlled approaches to Post Oak Tritt Rd. These delays are classified as level-of-service “B” in
the morning and “C” in the evening with less than 20 second wait times on average for vehicles
during the peak, which is within industry standards. Operations at these intersections will only
see minor increases in wait times with the addition of the school traffic.
Delays are seen on the site driveway for exiting traffic in the morning (34 seconds on average)
but are within industry standards (LOS “D” or better). Stacking is anticipated to be 4-5 vehicles
long. The afternoon peak when school traffic is leaving (3-4pm) will see similar delays as in the
morning peak, though stacking at the stop sign is slightly higher at 5-6 vehicles in length.
Moderate delays are expected for traffic exiting the site driveway during the evening peak (24
seconds on average) with queues of a 2-3 vehicles.
